1591wakeup-source”j␅ )R”(Œ␈required”‰Œ␄type”Œ␇boolean”Œ␋description”X_␁ Property to identify that a device can be used as wake up source.
1592
1593When this property is provided a specific flag is set into the
1594device that tells the system that the device is capable of
1595wake up the system.
1596

1598the system) by default but they can be enabled at runtime if necessary.

1783”uŒ␎#address-cells”j␅ )R”(Œ␈required”ˆŒ␅const”K␁Œ␄type”Œ␃int”Œ␋description”Œ'number of address cells in reg property”uŒ␋#size-cells”j␅ )R”(Œ␈required”ˆŒ␅const”K Œ␄type”Œ␃int”Œ␋description”Œ$number of size cells in reg property”uŒ␅label”j␅ )R”(Œ␈required”ˆŒ␄type”Œ␆string”Œ␋description”ŒSHuman readable string describing the device (used as device_get_binding() argument)”uŒ␈cs-gpios”j␅ )R”(Œ␄type”Œ
1784phandle-array”Œ␈required”‰Œ␋description”X␄ An array of chip select GPIOs to use. Each element
1785in the array specifies a GPIO. The index in the array
1786corresponds to the child node that the CS gpio controls.
1787
1788Example:
1789
1790 spi@... {
1791 cs-gpios = <&gpio0 23 GPIO_ACTIVE_LOW>,
1792 <&gpio1 10 GPIO_ACTIVE_LOW>,
1793 ...;
1794
1795 spi-device@0 {
1796 reg = <0>;
1797 ...
1798 };
1799 spi-device@1 {
1800 reg = <1>;
1801 ...
1802 };
1803 ...
1804 };
1805
1806The child node "spi-device@0" specifies a SPI device with
1807chip select controller gpio0, pin 23, and devicetree
1808GPIO flags GPIO_ACTIVE_LOW. Similarly, "spi-device@1" has CS GPIO
1809controller gpio1, pin 10, and flags GPIO_ACTIVE_LOW. Additional
1810devices can be configured in the same way.
1811
1812If unsure about the flags cell, GPIO_ACTIVE_LOW is generally a safe
1813choice for a typical "CSn" pin. GPIO_ACTIVE_HIGH may be used if
1814intervening hardware inverts the signal to the peripheral device or
1815the line itself is active high.
1816
1817If this property is not defined, no chip select GPIOs are set.
1818SPI controllers with dedicated CS pins do not need to define
1819the cs-gpios property.

1974
1975This controls the 2.4 GHz radio transceiver on nRF5x
1976SoCs, which is available for use with Bluetooth, 802.15.4,
1977and proprietary wireless protocols (not all of these
1978protocols are available on all SoCs; consult the product
1979specifications for details).
1980
1981This binding is not relevant to the nRF91x baseband radio.
1982
1983Front-End Module (FEM) support
1984------------------------------
1985
1986External front-end modules are range extenders used for boosting
1987the link robustness and link budget of wireless SoCs. If your
1988system includes an external FEM, set it up in the devicetree using
1989this binding's 'fem' property, like this example:
1990
1991 &radio {
1992 fem = <&nrf_radio_fem>;
1993 };
1994
1995 nrf_radio_fem: my-fem {
1996 compatible = "...";
1997 ....
1998 };
1999
2000Currently supported "compatible" properties for the FEM node are:
2001
2002 - generic-fem-two-ctrl-pins
2003 - nordic,nrf21540-fem
2004
2005Refer to the bindings for these compatibles for more information
2006about how to configure the FEM.
2007
2008Direction Finding Extension
2009---------------------------
2010
2011Some radios support the Bluetooth Direction Finding Extension (DFE).
2012The 'dfe-supported' property will be set when it is available.
2013In this case, the 'dfegpio[n]-gpios' properties configure GPIO pins
2014to use to drive antenna switching.
2015
2016Each dfegpio[n]-gpios property which is set is used to initialize the
2017corresponding PSEL.DFEGPIO[n] register.
2018
2019None of the dfegpio[n]-gpios properties are marked 'required',
2020since which PSEL.DFEGPIO[n] registers will be used to drive
2021antenna switches depends on the use case. Nevertheless, at least two
2022antennas must be available to use DFE.
2023
2024That in turn means that at least one dfegpio[n]-gpios
2025property must be provided if DFE is used, to give the radio the
2026possibility to switch between two antennas. To use 12 antennas,
20274 GPIOs must be provided (since 4 GPIO pins support switching up to
202816 antennas).
2029
2030GPIOs are used in order, following the indices of the dfegpio[n]-gpios
2031properties. The order is important because it affects the mapping of
2032antenna switch patterns to GPIOs.
2033
2034Antenna switching patterns
2035--------------------------
2036
2037An antenna switching pattern is a binary number where each bit is
2038applied to a particular antenna GPIO pin. For example, the pattern
20390x3 means that antenna GPIOs at indexes 0 and 1 will be set, while
2040the following are left unset.
2041
2042The number of GPIOs specified with dfegpio[n]-gpios properties
2043affects the allowed pattern values. For example, when using four
2044GPIOs, the pattern count cannot be greater than 16, and the
2045maximum allowed value is 15.
2046
2047Antenna switch patterns are stored in DFE internal memory by
2048writes to the SWITCHPATTERN register. DFE handling code applies
2049antenna switch patterns during Constant Tone Extension (CTE)
2050receive (Angle of Arrival mode) or transmission (Angle of
2051Departure mode) procedure.
2052
2053DFE States
2054----------
2055
2056There are four states of DFE operation:
2057
2058* Idle: in this state, PDU transmission happens.
2059 DFE uses SWITCHPATTERN[0] to select the antenna in this state.
2060 (The 'dfe-pdu-antenna' property value described below is stored
2061 in SWITCHPATTERN[0] by the radio controller code.)
2062
2063* Guard: in this state, DFE prepares for reception or transmission
2064 of CTE. For this state, DFE selects the antenna by applying
2065 SWITCHPATTERN[1].
2066
2067* Reference: in this state, DFE starts to receive or transmit CTE.
2068 In AoA mode, DFE collects reference IQ samples. The selected
2069 antenna is the same as in the guard state.
2070
2071* Switch-sample: in this state, actual antenna switching happens.
2072 DFE selects antennas by applying SWITCHPATTERN[2..N]. If the
2073 number of switch-sample periods is greater than the number of
2074 stored switching patterns, DFE loops back to SWITCHPATTERN[2].
2075”Œ
2076compatible”j—, Œ

Each LED in the group is
2176controlled by a GPIO. Each LED is defined in a child node of the
2177gpio-leds node.
2178
2179Here is an example which defines three LEDs in the node /leds:
2180
2181/ {
2182 leds {
2183 compatible = "gpio-leds";
2184 led_0 {
2185 gpios = <&gpio0 1 GPIO_ACTIVE_LOW>;
2186 };
2187 led_1 {
2188 gpios = <&gpio0 2 GPIO_ACTIVE_HIGH>;
2189 };
2190 led_2 {
2191 gpios = <&gpio1 15 (GPIO_PULL_UP | GPIO_ACTIVE_LOW)>;
2192 };
2193 };
2194};
2195
2196Above:
2197
2198- led_0 is pin 1 on gpio0. The LED is on when the pin is low,
2199 and off when the pin is high.
2200- led_1 is pin 2 on gpio0. The LED is on when the pin is high,
2201 and off when it is low.
2202- led_2 is pin 15 on gpio1. The LED is on when the pin is low,
2203 and the pin's internal pull-up resistor should be enabled.

2227”uŒ␏gpio-controller”j␅ )R”(Œ␄type”Œ␇boolean”Œ␈required”ˆŒ␋description”Œ'Convey's this node is a GPIO controller”uŒ␆ngpios”j␅ )R”(Œ␄type”Œ␃int”Œ␈required”‰Œ␇default”K Œ␋description”Xh␂ This property indicates the number of in-use slots of available slots
2228for GPIOs. The typical example is something like this: the hardware
2229register is 32 bits wide, but only 18 of the bits have a physical
2230counterpart. The driver is generally written so that all 32 bits can
2231be used, but the IP block is reused in a lot of designs, some using
2232all 32 bits, some using 18 and some using 12. In this case, setting
2233"ngpios = <18>;" informs the driver that only the first 18 GPIOs, at
2234local offset 0 .. 17, are in use. For cases in which there might be
2235holes in the slot range, this value should be the max slot number-1.
2236”uŒ␔gpio-reserved-ranges”j␅ )R”(Œ␄type”Œ␅array”Œ␈required”‰Œ␋description”X{␁ If not all the GPIOs at offsets 0...N-1 are usable for ngpios = <N>, then
2237this property contains an additional set of tuples which specify which GPIOs
2238are unusable. This property indicates the start and size of the GPIOs
2239that can't be used.
2240
2241For example, setting "gpio-reserved-ranges = <3 2>, <10 1>;" means that
2242GPIO offsets 3, 4, and 10 are not usable, even if ngpios = <18>.

22951 j␛% Nj␜% j␅ )R”(j␒1 j␟% )”}”(j"% j␞1 j‚␅ j␒1 j#% j␓1 ubj␗1 j␟% )”}”(j"% j␞1 j‚␅ j␗1 j#% j␘1 ubujQ% j␅ )R”ubj␜% j␅ )R”jQ% j␅ )R”ubŒ␑arduino-header-r3”N†”jr$ )”}”(ju$ j␜ jv$ j␋ jw$ j␅ )R”(Œ␋description”X)␆ GPIO pins exposed on Arduino Uno (R3) headers.
2296
2297The Arduino Uno layout provides four headers, two each along
2298opposite edges of the board.
2299
2300Proceeding counter-clockwise:
2301* An 8-pin Power Supply header. No pins on this header are exposed
2302 by this binding.
2303* A 6-pin Analog Input header. This has analog input signals
2304 labeled from A0 at the top through A5 at the bottom.
2305* An 8-pin header (opposite Analog Input). This has digital input
2306 signals labeled from D0 at the bottom D7 at the top;
2307* A 10-pin header (opposite Power Supply). This has six additional
2308 digital input signals labelled from D8 at the bottom through D13
2309 towards the top, skipping two pins, then finishing with D14 and
2310 D15 at the top.
2311
2312This binding provides a nexus mapping for 20 pins where parent pins 0
2313through 5 correspond to A0 through A5, and parent pins 6 through 21
2314correspond to D0 through D15, as depicted below:
2315
2316 D15 21
2317 D14 20
2318 AREF -
2319 GND -
2320 - N/C D13 19
2321 - IOREF D12 18
2322 - RESET D11 17
2323 - 3V3 D10 16
2324 - 5V D9 15
2325 - GND D8 14
2326 - GND
2327 - VIN D7 13
2328 D6 12
2329 0 A0 D5 11
2330 1 A1 D4 10
2331 2 A2 D3 9
2332 3 A3 D2 8
2333 4 A4 D1 7
2334 5 A5 D0 6

2506wakeup-source”j␅ )R”(Œ␈required”‰Œ␄type”Œ␇boolean”Œ␋description”X_␁ Property to identify that a device can be used as wake up source.
2507
2508When this property is provided a specific flag is set into the
2509device that tells the system that the device is capable of
2510wake up the system.
2511
2512Wake up capable devices are disabled (interruptions will not wake up
2513the system) by default but they can be enabled at runtime if necessary.

2577wakeup-source”j␅ )R”(Œ␈required”‰Œ␄type”Œ␇boolean”Œ␋description”X_␁ Property to identify that a device can be used as wake up source.
2578
2579When this property is provided a specific flag is set into the
2580device that tells the system that the device is capable of
2581wake up the system.
2582
2583Wake up capable devices are disabled (interruptions will not wake up
2584the system) by default but they can be enabled at runtime if necessary.

2648wakeup-source”j␅ )R”(Œ␈required”‰Œ␄type”Œ␇boolean”Œ␋description”X_␁ Property to identify that a device can be used as wake up source.
2649
2650When this property is provided a specific flag is set into the
2651device that tells the system that the device is capable of
2652wake up the system.
2653

2655the system) by default but they can be enabled at runtime if necessary.

2733wakeup-source”j␅ )R”(Œ␈required”‰Œ␄type”Œ␇boolean”Œ␋description”X_␁ Property to identify that a device can be used as wake up source.

2794properties”j␅ )R”(Œ generator”j␅ )R”(Œ␄type”Œ␇phandle”Œ␈required”ˆŒ␋description”ŒEReference to TIMER or RTC instance for generating PWM output signals
2795”uŒ␏clock-prescaler”j␅ )R”(Œ␄type”Œ␃int”Œ␈required”ˆŒ␋description”ŒİClock prescaler for RTC or TIMER used for generating PWM output signals.
2796
2797RTC: needs to be set to 0, which gives 32768 Hz base clock for PWM
2798generation.
2799
2800TIMER: 16 MHz / 2^prescaler base clock is used for PWM generation.
2801”uŒ
2802channel-gpios”j␅ )R”(Œ␄type”Œ
2803phandle-array”Œ␈required”ˆŒ␋description”X␞␄ An array of GPIOs assigned as outputs for the PWM channels. The number
2804of items in this array determines the number of channels that this PWM
2805will provide. This value is limited by the number of compare registers
2806in the used RTC/TIMER instance minus 1.
2807
2808Example:
2809
2810 sw_pwm: sw-pwm {
2811 compatible = "nordic,nrf-sw-pwm";
2812 ...
2813 channel-gpios = <&gpio0 20 GPIO_ACTIVE_HIGH>,
2814 <&gpio1 12 GPIO_ACTIVE_HIGH>;
2815 ...
2816 };
2817
2818The above will assign P0.20 as the output for channel 0 and P1.12 as
2819the output for channel 1. Both outputs will be initially configured as
2820active high.
2821
2822Please note that in the flags cell (the last component of each item
2823of the array) only the GPIO flags that specify the active level are
2824taken into account (any others are ignored), and they are used only
2825when the initial (inactive) state of the outputs is set.
2826After any PWM signal generation is requested for a given channel,
2827the polarity of its output is determined by the flag specified
2828in the request, i.e. PWM_POLARITY_INVERTED or PWM_POLARITY_NORMAL.

2948wakeup-source”j␅ )R”(Œ␈required”‰Œ␄type”Œ␇boolean”Œ␋description”X_␁ Property to identify that a device can be used as wake up source.
2949
2950When this property is provided a specific flag is set into the
2951device that tells the system that the device is capable of
2952wake up the system.
2953
2954Wake up capable devices are disabled (interruptions will not wake up
2955the system) by default but they can be enabled at runtime if necessary.
2956”uŒ␌power-domain”j␅ )R”(Œ␈required”‰Œ␄type”Œ␇phandle”Œ␋description”Œ†

2958
2959The device will be notified when the power domain it belongs to is either
2960suspended or resumed.
2961”uuuj␛% Nj␜% j␅ )R”(j³A j␟% )”}”(j"% j«A j‚␅ j³A j#% j´A ubjºA j␟% )”}”(j"% j«A j‚␅ jºA j#% j»A ubjÁA j␟% )”}”(j"% j«A j‚␅ jÁA j#% jÂA j(% ]”(jÊA jËA jÌA jÍA jÎA Œ␈fail_sss”ej+% ˆj,% ˆubjĞA j␟% )”}”(j"% j«A j‚␅ jĞA j#% jÑA ubj×A j␟% )”}”(j"% j«A j‚␅ j×A j#% jØA ubjŞA j␟% )”}”(j"% j«A j‚␅ jŞA j#% jßA ubjåA j␟% )”}”(j"% j«A j‚␅ jåA j#% jæA ubjìA j␟% )”}”(j"% j«A j‚␅ jìA j#% jíA ubjóA j␟% )”}”(j"% j«A j‚␅ jóA j#% jôA ubjúA j␟% )”}”(j"% j«A j‚␅ júA j#% jûA ubj␁B j␟% )”}”(j"% j«A j‚␅ j␁B j#% j␂B ubj␈B j␟% )”}”(j"% j«A j‚␅ j␈B j#% j B ubj␏B j␟% )”}”(j"% j«A j‚␅ j␏B j#% j␐B ubj␖B j␟% )”}”(j"% j«A j‚␅ j␖B j#% j␗B ubj␝B j␟% )”}”(j"% j«A j‚␅ j␝B j#% j␞B ubj$B j␟% )”}”(j"% j«A j‚␅ j$B j#% j%B ubj+B j␟% )”}”(j"% j«A j‚␅ j+B j#% j,B ubj2B j␟% )”}”(j"% j«A j‚␅ j2B j#% j3B ubj;B j␟% )”}”(j"% j«A j‚␅ j;B j#% j<B ubjBB j␟% )”}”(j"% j«A j‚␅ jBB j#% jCB ubjIB j␟% )”}”(j"% j«A j‚␅ jIB j#% jJB ubujQ% j␅ )R”ubŒ␒nordic,nrf-pinctrl”N†”jr$ )”}”(ju$ jã jv$ j␋ jw$ j␅ )R”(Œ␋description”Xè The nRF pin controller is a singleton node responsible for controlling
2962pin function selection and pin properties. For example, you can use this
2963node to route UART0 RX to pin P0.1 and enable the pull-up resistor on the
2964pin.
2965
2966The node has the 'pinctrl' node label set in your SoC's devicetree,
2967so you can modify it like this:
2968
2969 &pinctrl {
2970 /* your modifications go here */
2971 };
2972
2973All device pin configurations should be placed in child nodes of the
2974'pinctrl' node, as shown in this example:
2975
2976 /* You can put this in places like a board-pinctrl.dtsi file in
2977 * your board directory, or a devicetree overlay in your application.
2978 */
2979 &pinctrl {
2980 /* configuration for uart0 device, default state */
2981 uart0_default: uart0_default {
2982 /* group 1 ('group1' name is arbitrary) */
2983 group1 {
2984 /* configure P0.1 as UART_TX and P0.2 as UART_RTS */
2985 psels = <NRF_PSEL(UART_TX, 0, 1)>, <NRF_PSEL(UART_RTS, 0, 2)>;
2986 };
2987 /* group 2 */
2988 group2 {
2989 /* configure P0.3 as UART_RX and P0.4 as UART_CTS */
2990 psels = <NRF_PSEL(UART_RX, 0, 3)>, <NRF_PSEL(UART_CTS, 0, 4)>;
2991 /* both P0.3 and P0.4 are configured with pull-up */
2992 bias-pull-up;
2993 };
2994 };
2995 };
2996
2997The 'uart0_default' child node encodes the pin configurations for a
2998particular state of a device; in this case, the default (that is, active)
2999state. You would specify the low-power configuration for the same device
3000in a separate child node.
3001
3002As shown, pin configurations are organized in groups within each child node.
3003Each group can specify a list of pin function selections in the 'psels'
3004property. The NRF_PSEL macro is used to specify a pin function selection.
3005Available pin functions can be found in the
3006include/dt-bindings/pinctrl/nrf-pinctrl.h header file.
3007
3008A group can also specify shared pin properties common to all the specified
3009pins, such as the 'bias-pull-up' property in group 2. Here is a list of
3010supported standard pin properties:
3011
3012- bias-disable: Disable pull-up/down (default behavior, not required).
3013- bias-pull-up: Enable pull-up resistor.
3014- bias-pull-down: Enable pull-down resistor.
3015- low-power-enable: Configure pin as an input with input buffer
3016 disconnected.
3017
3018Note that bias options are mutually exclusive.
3019
3020To link this pin configuration with a device, use a pinctrl-N property
3021for some number N, like this example you could place in your board's DTS
3022file:
3023
3024 #include "board-pinctrl.dtsi"
3025
3026 &uart0 {
3027 pinctrl-0 = <&uart0_default>;
3028 pinctrl-names = "default";
3029 };

3306wakeup-source”j␅ )R”(Œ␈required”‰Œ␄type”Œ␇boolean”Œ␋description”X_␁ Property to identify that a device can be used as wake up source.

3309device that tells the system that the device is capable of

3319”uŒ␎requires-ulbpr”j␅ )R”(Œ␄type”Œ␇boolean”Œ␈required”‰Œ␋description”X␗␁ Indicates the device requires the ULBPR (0x98) command.
3320
3321Some flash chips such as the Microchip SST26VF series have a block
3322protection register that initializes to write-protected. Use this

3325”uŒ␇has-dpd”j␅ )R”(Œ␄type”Œ␇boolean”Œ␈required”‰Œ␋description”X¡␁ Indicates the device supports the DPD (0xB9) command.
3326
3327Use this property to indicate the flash chip supports the Deep
3328Power-Down mode that is entered by command 0xB9 to reduce power
3329consumption below normal standby levels. Use of this property
3330implies that the RDPD (0xAB) Release from Deep Power Down command
3331is also supported. (On some chips this command functions as Read
3332Electronic Signature; see t-enter-dpd).
3333”uŒ␓dpd-wakeup-sequence”j␅ )R”(Œ␄type”Œ␅array”Œ␈required”‰Œ␋description”XF␂ Specifies wakeup durations for devices without RDPD.
3334
3335Some devices (Macronix MX25R in particular) wake from deep power
3336down by a timed sequence of CSn toggles rather than the RDPD
3337command. This property specifies three durations measured in
3338nanoseconds, in this order:
3339(1) tDPDD (Delay Time for Release from Deep Power-Down Mode)
3340(2) tCDRP (CSn Toggling Time before Release from Deep Power-Down Mode)
3341(3) tRDP (Recovery Time for Release from Deep Power-Down Mode)
3342
3343Absence of this property indicates that the RDPD command should be
3344used to wake the chip from Deep Power-Down mode.
3345”uŒ␋t-enter-dpd”j␅ )R”(Œ␄type”Œ␃int”Œ␈required”‰Œ␋description”ŒóDuration required to complete the DPD command.
3346
3347This provides the duration, in nanoseconds, that CSn must be
3348remain deasserted after issuing DPD before the chip will enter
3349deep power down.
3350
3351If not provided the driver does not enforce a delay.
3352”uŒ
3353t-exit-dpd”j␅ )R”(Œ␄type”Œ␃int”Œ␈required”‰Œ␋description”X ␁ Duration required to complete the RDPD command.
3354
3355This provides the duration, in nanoseconds, that CSn must be
3356remain deasserted after issuing RDPD before the chip will exit
3357deep power down and be ready to receive additional commands.
3358
3359If not provided the driver does not enforce a delay.
3360”uŒ␈has-lock”j␅ )R”(Œ␄type”Œ␃int”Œ␈required”‰Œ␋description”X␇␂ Bit mask of bits of the status register that should be cleared on
3361startup.
3362
3363Some devices from certain vendors power-up with block protect bits
3364set in the status register, which prevent any erase or program
3365operation from working. Devices that have this behavior need to
3366clear those bits on startup. However, other devices have
3367non-volatile bits in the status register that should not be
3368cleared.
3369
3370This value, when present, identifies bits in the status register
3371that should be cleared when the device is initialized.

3377”uŒ␐enter-4byte-addr”j␅ )R”(Œ␄type”Œ␃int”Œ␈required”‰Œ␋description”Xe␂ Enter 4-Byte Addressing value from JESD216 BFP DW16
3378

3487”uuuj␛% Nj␜% j␅ )R”(j€L j␟% )”}”(j"% jxL j‚␅ j€L j#% jL ubj‡L j␟% )”}”(j"% jxL j‚␅ j‡L j#% jˆL ubjL j␟% )”}”(j"% jxL j‚␅ jL j#% jL ubj•L j␟% )”}”(j"% jxL j‚␅ j•L j#% j–L j(% ]”(jL jŸL j L j¡L j¢L Œ␈fail_sss”ej+% ˆj,% ˆubj¤L j␟% )”}”(j"% jxL j‚␅ j¤L j#% j¥L ubj«L j␟% )”}”(j"% jxL j‚␅ j«L j#% j¬L ubj²L j␟% )”}”(j"% jxL j‚␅ j²L j#% j³L ubj¹L j␟% )”}”(j"% jxL j‚␅ j¹L j#% jºL ubjÀL j␟% )”}”(j"% jxL j‚␅ jÀL j#% jÁL ubjÇL j␟% )”}”(j"% jxL j‚␅ jÇL j#% jÈL ubjÎL j␟% )”}”(j"% jxL j‚␅ jÎL j#% jÏL ubjÕL j␟% )”}”(j"% jxL j‚␅ jÕL j#% jÖL ubjÜL j␟% )”}”(j"% jxL j‚␅ jÜL j#% jİL ubjãL j␟% )”}”(j"% jxL j‚␅ jãL j#% jäL ubjêL j␟% )”}”(j"% jxL j‚␅ jêL j#% jëL ubjñL j␟% )”}”(j"% jxL j‚␅ jñL j#% jòL ubjøL j␟% )”}”(j"% jxL j‚␅ jøL j#% jùL ubjÿL j␟% )”}”(j"% jxL j‚␅ jÿL j#% j M ubj␈M j␟% )”}”(j"% jxL j‚␅ j␈M j#% j M ubj␏M j␟% )”}”(j"% jxL j‚␅ j␏M j#% j␐M ubj␖M j␟% )”}”(j"% jxL j‚␅ j␖M j#% j␗M ubujQ% j␅ )R”ubŒ␎nordic,nrf-twi”N†”jr$ )”}”(ju$ j␟ jv$ j␋ jw$ j␅ )R”(Œ␋description”XH␅ Nordic nRF family TWI (TWI master).
3488
3489This binding can be used for nodes which can represent TWI
3490peripherals. When a single SoC peripheral ID corresponds to multiple
3491I2C peripherals (like TWI or TWIM), the corresponding devicetree
3492nodes must be set up to select TWI before use.
3493
3494To select TWI, set the node's "compatible" to "nordic,nrf-twi" and
3495its "status" to "okay", e.g. using an overlay file like this:
3496
3497 /* This is for TWI0 -- change to "i2c1" for TWI1. */
3498 &i2c0 {
3499 compatible = "nordic,nrf-twi";
3500 status = "okay";
3501 /* other property settings can go here */
3502 };
3503
3504You can use either of these options to check TWI availability on
3505your SoC:
3506
3507 1. Check the peripheral Instantiation table in the Memory
3508 section of your SoC's Product Specification document.
3509 A "TWI0" instance in the table means "i2c0" in the devicetree
3510 can be used with this binding, and similarly for "TWI1".
3511
3512 2. Open your SoC's .dtsi file and look for a node definition that
3513 documents TWI support, like this:
3514
3515 i2c0: i2c@40003000 {
3516 /*
3517 * This i2c node can be TWI, [...].
3518 */
3519 ...
3520 };
3521
3522 If your SoC only has TWIM and TWIS I2C peripherals, you cannot use
3523 this binding. See the "nordic,nrf-twim" binding instead.
3524”Œ

3527interrupts”j␅ )R”(Œ␈required”ˆŒ␄type”Œ␅array”Œ␋description”Œ␕interrupts for device”uŒ␇sda-pin”j␅ )R”(Œ␄type”Œ␃int”Œ␈required”‰Œ␋description”X‚␁ IMPORTANT: This option will only be used if the new pin control driver
3528is not enabled. It will be deprecated in the future.
3529
3530The SDA pin to use.
3531
3532For pins P0.0 through P0.31, use the pin number. For example,
3533to use P0.16 for SDA, set:
3534
3535 sda-pin = <16>;
3536
3537For pins P1.0 through P1.31, add 32 to the pin number. For
3538example, to use P1.2 for SDA, set:
3539
3540 sda-pin = <34>; /* 32 + 2 */

3627
3628The reg property describes two register blocks: one for the memory
3629corresponding to the QSPI peripheral registers, and another for
3630the memory mapped XIP area:
3631
3632 qspi: qspi@2b000 {
3633 compatible = "nordic,nrf-qspi";
3634 reg = <0x2b000 0x1000>, <0x10000000 0x10000000>;
3635 reg-names = "qspi", "qspi_mm";
3636 ...
3637 };
3638
3639Above, the register block with base address 0x2b000 and name
3640"qspi" are the QSPI peripheral registers. The register block with
3641base address 0x10000000 and name "qspi_mm" is the XIP area.
